00:00:06,090 --> 00:00:09,211
Hello, welcome to Sewing, a Musical Patchwork,

2
00:00:09,451 --> 00:00:11,532
the Music of Sackboy, A Big Adventure.

3
00:00:13,233 --> 00:00:14,013
I'm Jay Waters.

4
00:00:14,333 --> 00:00:17,475
I'm the game's audio director based over at Sumo Sheffield.

5
00:00:17,495 --> 00:00:20,616
Hi, I'm Joe Thwaites.

6
00:00:20,716 --> 00:00:24,078
I'm principal composer and music producer from PlayStation's

7
00:00:24,158 --> 00:00:25,038
Creative Arts team.

8
00:00:26,419 --> 00:00:29,260
And I'm James Marshall, music supervisor on this project,

9
00:00:29,460 --> 00:00:31,181
also from the Creative Arts team.

10
00:00:34,858 --> 00:00:38,701
We've been really pleased to see such amazing feedback since the release of Sackboy,

11
00:00:39,101 --> 00:00:41,082
a great deal of that with regards to the music.

12
00:00:41,823 --> 00:00:45,005
Today, we'll hopefully give you an insight into some of the decisions and methods

13
00:00:45,065 --> 00:00:47,887
behind the soundtrack, provide a little look under the hood,

14
00:00:48,467 --> 00:00:51,429
and also touch on how we used a diverse roster of tracks

15
00:00:51,849 --> 00:00:54,091
to help set the tone throughout the various worlds.

16
00:00:56,595 --> 00:01:00,038
I'm going to provide a deeper look into the practical approaches we took,

17
00:01:00,619 --> 00:01:04,963
including the creative and technical challenges with implementing music in-game

18
00:01:05,423 --> 00:01:07,164
and composing a theme for the game.

19
00:01:08,526 --> 00:01:13,690
And we'll also look at how the overall brief led to new ways of using licensed and bespoke music,

20
00:01:14,050 --> 00:01:18,254
ultimately tying together many threads to make a cohesive experience for the players.

21
00:01:22,257 --> 00:01:25,040
Starting with a look back at the previous titles in the franchise,

22
00:01:25,580 --> 00:01:28,361
We examined what the core components of the soundtracks were,

23
00:01:29,041 --> 00:01:32,442
many of them centred around the concept of play, create, share,

24
00:01:32,862 --> 00:01:34,983
and its support for user-generated content.

25
00:01:36,023 --> 00:01:39,364
What this meant was that interactive music needed to have a simple system

26
00:01:39,684 --> 00:01:42,545
that could be easily implemented by players in their own creations.

27
00:01:43,245 --> 00:01:46,867
It also meant that licensed music generally remained a linear experience.

28
00:01:48,533 --> 00:01:53,014
And as Jay mentioned, the franchise is well known for the play, create, share concept,

29
00:01:53,054 --> 00:01:59,436
but we wanted to focus solely on play and that allowed us to keep the balance of licensed and composed music,

30
00:01:59,796 --> 00:02:04,496
but meant we had a greater chance of a curated approach when it came to selecting the music itself.

31
00:02:07,817 --> 00:02:13,038
So without these limitations, moving forward meant we were able to explore a much more narrative led soundtrack,

32
00:02:13,618 --> 00:02:18,139
focusing more on thematic materials such as world themes, characters and story beats.

33
00:02:19,405 --> 00:02:24,188
We also had a much bigger game to think about, with the level count hitting over 90 in total.

34
00:02:26,650 --> 00:02:31,873
We also had a change from composed levels, where a composer would look just after a specific level

35
00:02:31,933 --> 00:02:36,856
or section of the game, to composer curators, where a composer's sound would actually influence

36
00:02:36,916 --> 00:02:39,078
the whole of that music of that world.

37
00:02:40,687 --> 00:02:45,671
And we also wanted to move away from just dropping in licensed tracks wholesale and take a more

38
00:02:45,751 --> 00:02:51,495
detailed deep implementation approach where each track fit a level aligning the licensed music

39
00:02:51,655 --> 00:02:59,982
with the detail we can obtain from a composed score. When we first began talking to the folks

40
00:03:00,022 --> 00:03:05,786
at Creative Arts Team we took with us a deck of audio goals. This particular slide served as an

41
00:03:05,866 --> 00:03:07,007
ideal jumping off point.

42
00:03:07,886 --> 00:03:11,887
Obviously this touches on more than just music here, but it gives a good idea of some of the

43
00:03:11,927 --> 00:03:17,169
higher level ambitions we had for the franchise. First and foremost we wanted to support the art

44
00:03:17,189 --> 00:03:22,511
direction as best we could, the concept of which was a crafted world imagined by a child.

45
00:03:23,272 --> 00:03:27,993
Fantastic Meets the Familiar was the general strap line with worlds set within real world

46
00:03:28,033 --> 00:03:32,895
environments and playing host to imaginary locations crafted by a child at play.

47
00:03:33,925 --> 00:03:37,947
Through the sound, we wanted to support this by utilizing tangible objects

48
00:03:38,147 --> 00:03:42,168
and accessible source material combined with added layers of imagination.

49
00:03:44,288 --> 00:03:47,569
We also wanted to look at ways in which we could somehow marry the sound design

50
00:03:47,609 --> 00:03:48,870
more closely with the music.

51
00:03:49,490 --> 00:03:51,991
We wanted to bring a certain harmony to the game's worlds.

52
00:03:52,411 --> 00:03:56,012
We were looking to do this by taking a music first approach to sound design.

53
00:03:56,832 --> 00:03:59,733
This meaning that any tonal or potentially musical elements

54
00:03:59,773 --> 00:04:03,034
of the sound effects we wanted to treat more as musical instruments.

55
00:04:03,723 --> 00:04:05,485
We'll touch a bit more on this a little later.

56
00:04:08,006 --> 00:04:12,789
Unsurprisingly, we really wanted to push towards assembling a really groundbreaking soundtrack.

57
00:04:13,330 --> 00:04:19,273
We wanted to investigate ways in which we could revolutionise implementation of licensed music.

58
00:04:19,894 --> 00:04:25,877
And we wanted to further push the franchise's trademark eclectic mix by expanding it in all directions.

59
00:04:28,039 --> 00:04:33,182
And finally, we wanted to look at ways in which we could further innovate development of the franchise's identity.

60
00:04:33,824 --> 00:04:38,749
paying close attention to attention to its subtlety, nuance and attention to detail,

61
00:04:39,210 --> 00:04:41,913
its immersive world full of charm, joy and humour,

62
00:04:42,554 --> 00:04:44,936
as well as its unique juxtaposition of concepts.

63
00:04:48,420 --> 00:04:50,882
Following this up, we presented them with a wish list

64
00:04:51,183 --> 00:04:53,986
detailing some of the musical content we wanted to explore.

65
00:04:55,975 --> 00:05:00,556
Starting off, major artists, something that will be fairly new territory for the game,

66
00:05:01,016 --> 00:05:04,497
and aligning with the drive towards a more AAA game experience.

67
00:05:05,117 --> 00:05:10,299
This time we really wanted to raise the bar in terms of securing more mainstream and recognisable artists.

68
00:05:12,419 --> 00:05:18,641
And artist exclusives, an area we experimented with on LBP3, and we're keen to develop further in this game,

69
00:05:19,201 --> 00:05:23,723
working in close collaboration with established artists in the composition of bespoke music.

70
00:05:26,060 --> 00:05:34,030
Classics. We also saw great potential in the use of more vintage material and were keen to experiment with interactive implementation where possible.

71
00:05:35,652 --> 00:05:44,763
Similarly, with covers, we had a number of ideas for expanding the use of covers, selecting original arrangements of classic songs or commissioning somewhat more unique approaches.

72
00:05:47,611 --> 00:05:53,012
Quite befitting of the game's general aesthetic, we were keen to explore interesting and effective use of mashup tracks,

73
00:05:53,553 --> 00:05:58,334
in particular the prospect of using existing level music in interesting new combinations.

74
00:06:00,355 --> 00:06:03,835
We also wanted to push further to discover more niche artists and performers,

75
00:06:04,356 --> 00:06:06,456
something for which the franchise is now synonymous.

76
00:06:08,757 --> 00:06:10,877
And above all, we just wanted to have some fun,

77
00:06:11,258 --> 00:06:14,418
striving for opportunities that might raise a smile or two from the player.

78
00:06:18,440 --> 00:06:23,522
So from the start of the project, we had a rough outline of the overall structure of the game.

79
00:06:23,702 --> 00:06:26,963
We had a set of distinct worlds, which you can see on this slide here,

80
00:06:27,483 --> 00:06:30,784
each with their own art style, gameplay mechanics, narrative hooks.

81
00:06:31,324 --> 00:06:34,565
We had a general outline of the types of levels that would be in each world as well,

82
00:06:35,005 --> 00:06:41,547
from ride-ons to more exploratory, more open levels, side-scrollers, things like that.

83
00:06:42,479 --> 00:06:45,500
The team had already been working on prototypes for the music levels,

84
00:06:45,540 --> 00:06:46,800
which we're going to touch on later,

85
00:06:47,160 --> 00:06:49,400
so we knew we had to include those across the game

86
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:51,541
with one per world where we could manage it.

87
00:06:52,421 --> 00:06:53,701
Jay also mentioned the covers,

88
00:06:53,741 --> 00:06:55,982
and this was another thing that we wanted to include

89
00:06:56,882 --> 00:07:01,343
throughout the game, but again on a one-per-world basis or so.

90
00:07:02,223 --> 00:07:04,203
With both of these, we knew we had to strike a balance

91
00:07:04,243 --> 00:07:05,944
that would keep the player surprised

92
00:07:05,984 --> 00:07:07,784
without oversaturating the concepts.

93
00:07:08,224 --> 00:07:10,004
Too many, and they'd become predictable.

94
00:07:10,364 --> 00:07:12,165
Too few, and they'd come across as a gimmick.

95
00:07:12,871 --> 00:07:14,452
The whole game then had to have through lines,

96
00:07:14,792 --> 00:07:18,453
so Joe is going to touch on that later when talking about thematic material.

97
00:07:19,033 --> 00:07:22,054
But we also had things such as cut scenes and a world map,

98
00:07:22,494 --> 00:07:25,956
which did the heavy lifting of taking these worlds with their disparate sound palettes

99
00:07:26,356 --> 00:07:29,557
and making them feel naturally cohesive across the project.

100
00:07:30,037 --> 00:07:33,778
So let's have a look at some of these levels and worlds themselves.

101
00:07:46,101 --> 00:07:49,482
So the worlds were fairly archetypal when it came to design.

102
00:07:50,342 --> 00:07:57,204
You had a water world, a world set in space, but we knew with the esoteric nature of the franchise

103
00:07:57,244 --> 00:08:01,445
we could take things in a different direction. This first world, which you can see concept art

104
00:08:01,505 --> 00:08:04,646
for here, is set across a Tibetan-esque mountaintop.

105
00:08:05,477 --> 00:08:10,759
The art design itself incorporates eastern elements, so it was a logical step to look for music which did the same.

106
00:08:11,460 --> 00:08:15,942
Anderlea, a lot of alternative and psychedelic music, shares that similar kind of sound palette,

107
00:08:16,383 --> 00:08:20,145
and these were the types of songs many fans associated with the franchise.

108
00:08:20,745 --> 00:08:26,048
You can hear in this particular track certain instrumentation which fit this brief.

109
00:08:26,773 --> 00:08:29,515
And by having it as the first set of music encountered,

110
00:08:30,056 --> 00:08:32,758
with its bright, inviting, and lively beat,

111
00:08:33,358 --> 00:08:35,400
not only did it thematically fit the design,

112
00:08:35,880 --> 00:08:40,064
it also acted as a reassuring familiarity for longtime fans of the series.

113
00:08:41,224 --> 00:08:44,867
Moving to the colossal canopy, our Amazon-esque world.

114
00:08:55,973 --> 00:08:59,055
So you can hear here with this great track by Brian D'Oliveira,

115
00:09:00,156 --> 00:09:06,940
it's incorporating tribal drums, organic instrumentation, you've got a very, very

116
00:09:07,160 --> 00:09:11,343
subtle element of ethnotronica in there, which was another thing that we looked at when we

117
00:09:11,363 --> 00:09:16,566
looked at this particular world. And given that there were a lot of elements from South America,

118
00:09:17,087 --> 00:09:21,550
we brought those inspirations in to give it a real kind of carnival vibe as well.

119
00:09:24,567 --> 00:09:26,648
Moving to the Undersea World,

120
00:09:31,252 --> 00:09:35,716
and this very jazzy cover of Grieg reinterpreted by Jim Fowler.

121
00:09:39,780 --> 00:09:43,943
The Kingdom of Krablantus was a world featuring lots and lots of

122
00:09:44,223 --> 00:09:47,106
antique furniture in the background and these lush textures.

123
00:09:47,937 --> 00:09:52,220
And this particular set dressing inspired us to look at older styles of music,

124
00:09:52,700 --> 00:09:58,623
so classical, jazz, swing, and then often putting our own contemporary spin on things.

125
00:09:59,043 --> 00:10:03,906
And you can hear that with this new interpretation of a classical piece.

126
00:10:09,388 --> 00:10:14,011
We then also went in completely the opposite direction at the interstellar junction.

127
00:10:20,045 --> 00:10:23,086
And you can hear with this track, it's synths, synths and more synths.

128
00:10:31,009 --> 00:10:35,470
This was one of our checkboxes ticked with an artist exclusive

129
00:10:35,590 --> 00:10:37,691
by the Glitch Shop producer Opio.

130
00:10:39,371 --> 00:10:42,272
And this aesthetic went throughout the space world

131
00:10:42,352 --> 00:10:44,133
where it was electronic music.

132
00:10:44,877 --> 00:10:49,099
almost a history of electronic music as you went through the world itself,

133
00:10:49,920 --> 00:10:54,362
with synths, beats, breaks, and a slightly darker edge

134
00:10:55,723 --> 00:10:59,746
as things are heating up for Sackboy as he makes his way through his adventure.

135
00:11:02,227 --> 00:11:03,048
And then lastly...

136
00:11:07,470 --> 00:11:11,633
the final world, the center of QWAF World, with its previous...

137
00:11:12,614 --> 00:11:18,117
designs of all the assets from previous worlds mixed together in a chaotic maelstrom by the

138
00:11:18,157 --> 00:11:23,679
antagonist Vex. So we looked at that for inspiration and in this remix from 2Metalo

139
00:11:26,720 --> 00:11:34,884
you can hear it's not only playfully malevolent but it also takes eight or so tracks previously

140
00:11:35,084 --> 00:11:40,326
used throughout the game and makes a mashup again ticking a box that we wanted to achieve.

141
00:11:42,554 --> 00:11:49,741
to create this delightfully demonic but very very funky mashup. And we were always considering the

142
00:11:49,781 --> 00:11:54,366
level design when it came to the music and always looking for opportunities where music and visuals

143
00:11:54,807 --> 00:12:02,655
would inform each other. But how did we select the songs for those levels? It all began

144
00:12:03,334 --> 00:12:08,038
with a massive playlist of around 100 or so songs,

145
00:12:08,778 --> 00:12:10,660
an extensive collection of anything we could think

146
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:12,241
would possibly work for a world.

147
00:12:12,661 --> 00:12:14,743
It was more of a wishlist than anyone could feed in

148
00:12:14,783 --> 00:12:17,505
with what they wanted to possibly hear in the game.

149
00:12:18,258 --> 00:12:19,899
And then as the levels were blocked out,

150
00:12:20,059 --> 00:12:23,700
we placed them in their earliest form to gauge the general vibe.

151
00:12:24,020 --> 00:12:28,982
This allowed us to create a smaller subset of songs with about 20 to 30.

152
00:12:29,602 --> 00:12:32,424
And it was here where we looked at what the general vibe of the level was.

153
00:12:32,464 --> 00:12:36,545
Was it going to be fast-paced, a bit more chaotic, or something more laid back?

154
00:12:36,965 --> 00:12:40,147
Did it have a set trajectory, like on rails levels?

155
00:12:40,247 --> 00:12:44,448
Or was it a bit more free form, allowing the player to explore at their own will?

156
00:12:45,045 --> 00:12:51,529
The former was easier to anticipate how a track might play out as the general time between A and B

157
00:12:51,969 --> 00:12:56,012
was going to be pretty much similar throughout the level. But levels that were more freeform

158
00:12:56,332 --> 00:13:01,796
and had a hub area required a different approach as players could spend a lot of time in one area

159
00:13:01,936 --> 00:13:07,980
or they could go in random order between different sections of the level. So this allowed us to gauge

160
00:13:08,160 --> 00:13:11,642
whether the level was going to be more suited for a composed or a licensed track.

161
00:13:12,565 --> 00:13:16,728
If a license track looked like it would work, we'd find those which tick the correct boxes.

162
00:13:17,448 --> 00:13:22,311
Did it have the necessary files that we might be able to use? Was it likely to be in budget?

163
00:13:23,432 --> 00:13:29,096
Once we had these, we would go out for approval on those particular tracks, and then approvals

164
00:13:29,136 --> 00:13:34,479
would come back depending on the request, which would give us around one or two songs

165
00:13:35,300 --> 00:13:38,862
that we could consider for the level. If it looked like the license track would work,

166
00:13:39,083 --> 00:13:40,263
implementation would start.

167
00:13:40,985 --> 00:13:46,570
If it looked like it would be more of a composed level, we'd start a brief, discuss it with the

168
00:13:46,590 --> 00:13:53,435
composer and begin that process. We did have one thing that helped us throughout the project. One

169
00:13:53,475 --> 00:13:59,780
challenge that we encountered earlier on is that music's extremely subjective and the particular

170
00:13:59,900 --> 00:14:04,764
process here involved a lot of stakeholders. As the importance of music grew throughout

171
00:14:04,784 --> 00:14:09,207
the project and developed, we created this flowchart in a bid to slightly substantiate

172
00:14:09,785 --> 00:14:15,634
the music choices as a way for us to make sure any songs that we considered met the criteria we needed for the game.

173
00:14:16,335 --> 00:14:21,564
This particular portion of the chart served as an initial check and was there to remove subjectivity.

174
00:14:22,627 --> 00:14:27,209
Given that Sackboy, with the type of game it is, there were a lot of songs that fit the vibe,

175
00:14:27,289 --> 00:14:34,113
but maybe they didn't tick the other boxes. So we'd look at the flowchart. If there was someone

176
00:14:34,133 --> 00:14:38,336
who was particularly attached to a song, we'd consult with the flowchart, refer back to it,

177
00:14:38,476 --> 00:14:43,239
and if it didn't tick the boxes, unfortunately, the song would be set aside. When it came to

178
00:14:43,279 --> 00:14:49,403
implementing, Joe's going to pick up on how that was used in terms of getting those songs in the

179
00:14:49,443 --> 00:14:49,603
game.

180
00:14:53,555 --> 00:14:59,139
James. As we mentioned, because of the heritage of the game, we knew that we wanted to incorporate

181
00:14:59,199 --> 00:15:03,202
licensed music and we also knew that we wanted to embed the music into the game

182
00:15:03,883 --> 00:15:07,065
in a way that was seamless and helped score each player's experience.

183
00:15:07,737 --> 00:15:17,566
So regardless of whether the track was composed or licensed, once we had the track that fitted the theme and the tone of the level, we needed to make sure a number of things.

184
00:15:18,006 --> 00:15:23,011
One, the track had enough variation to maintain interest for the duration of the level.

185
00:15:23,071 --> 00:15:29,356
We'd often find a track that would fit perfectly to the brief, but we soon realised that it didn't really move from one or two chord progressions.

186
00:15:29,416 --> 00:15:33,000
And within those chord progressions, if you take away the lyrics and the...

187
00:15:34,254 --> 00:15:38,557
of the vocals, it's not really going to go anywhere, so we need to go back to the drawing board.

188
00:15:39,277 --> 00:15:43,761
We also need to make sure that we had enough stems for the track so that we could rearrange

189
00:15:43,801 --> 00:15:48,344
and embellish the track to best fit it into the level. We had some great tracks that we

190
00:15:48,384 --> 00:15:52,647
couldn't use because we didn't have access to the stems, or it's an old track and the

191
00:15:52,687 --> 00:15:54,108
stems themselves didn't actually exist.

192
00:15:55,709 --> 00:16:00,031
And then we also needed to make sure that we had the rights to use it in the game how we wanted to use it.

193
00:16:00,211 --> 00:16:11,014
So the rights holders needed to be on board and give us permission to break the track up into the stems and use it in our implementation system.

194
00:16:14,964 --> 00:16:20,447
So once we had the track and its stems, we would begin our initial implementation.

195
00:16:20,547 --> 00:16:23,890
The goal here was to have a system where we could add the component parts of the track

196
00:16:24,650 --> 00:16:26,792
and the game would reconstruct these elements at runtime.

197
00:16:28,633 --> 00:16:31,095
It wouldn't matter if it was a licensed track or a composed track,

198
00:16:31,495 --> 00:16:33,296
they'd both be implemented in the same way.

199
00:16:33,930 --> 00:16:39,835
So we wanted each track to feel unique and change depending on the player's route or play style through the level.

200
00:16:40,176 --> 00:16:48,303
But most importantly, we wanted to connect with the narrative of the game and really help propel Sackboy's journey through the various levels in the game.

201
00:16:49,124 --> 00:16:57,552
So to do this, we had some general high-level systems and also some bespoke systems for individual levels to keep the music fresh and interesting throughout.

202
00:16:58,417 --> 00:17:03,819
So the basic system comprised of four implementation techniques, which many of you will be familiar with.

203
00:17:04,799 --> 00:17:14,863
Horizontal re-sequencing, which is this idea of splitting the track into multiple loopable chunks and then moving through them as you move through the game.

204
00:17:16,336 --> 00:17:20,603
Vertical layering, which is this idea of splitting each track into multiple layers

205
00:17:21,124 --> 00:17:22,947
that can be added and removed at runtime.

206
00:17:23,087 --> 00:17:26,934
So, you know, splitting it into drums, bass, vocals,

207
00:17:26,974 --> 00:17:29,719
and then bringing in the drums or the bass at certain points in the game.

208
00:17:31,251 --> 00:17:36,299
Stingers and embellishments, which were short musical elements that would be triggered by

209
00:17:36,539 --> 00:17:41,006
gameplay events, these kind of more instant things. If you get a pickup or something like

210
00:17:41,026 --> 00:17:45,713
that you get stinger or embellishments being kind of additional little bits of music that

211
00:17:45,733 --> 00:17:47,195
we add on to kind of license tracks.

212
00:17:48,582 --> 00:17:58,684
And finally, runtime processing, which was this idea of using filters and effects that manipulate the music at runtime, depending on what the player's doing.

213
00:17:59,244 --> 00:18:03,365
And I'm going to show a quick demo of each of those and how we use them in Sackboy.

